    <body>
        
        <div type="letter">
            <div type="text">
                <opener>
                    <placeName>Down, | Beckenham, Kent. | Railway station | Orpington. S.E.R.</placeName>
                    <date>Oct. 28. 79.</date>
                    <salute>Dear Sir,</salute>
                </opener>
                <div type="transcription">
                     
<p>I am much obliged for your interesting letter.<ref target="#foot.f1"/> The case is quite new to me, &amp; may perhaps explain other instances in which the magnificent colours in the wings of butterflies appear only from certain points of view. If you or any one had actually observed in Celebes<ref target="#foot.f2"/> the male approaching the female in the proper position for displaying his colours, the case would have been well worth publishing. When I next go to London I will look at this butterfly in the British Museum, that I may be able fully to appreciate your description. I will then perhaps give an account of your remarks in “Nature”.<ref target="#foot.f3"/></p>
<p>Dear Sir, | Yours faithfully &amp; obliged | Charles Darwin.</p> 
                </div>
            </div>

        </div>
        
        
        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1">See <ref target="./DCP-LETT-12254.xml">letter from Eduard Schulte, 23 October 1879</ref>.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f2">Celebes is now Sulawesi in Indonesia.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f3">The butterfly was <hi rend="italic">Hypolimnas bolina</hi>, the common eggfly (known to CD as <hi rend="italic">Diadema bolina</hi>). See <ref target="./DCP-LETT-12359.xml">letter to <hi rend="italic">Nature</hi>, 16 December 1879</ref>. CD next visited London from 3 to 11 December (<ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_1218.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Emma Darwin’s</ref> diary (DAR 242)).</note>
        </div>
    
